I'm so surprised I haven't written a review for Dua yet!  Dua is my husband's top favorite restaurant.  He went to school at GSU and took me to Dua for a lunch a few years ago, and we've been frequenting ever since.  I love their food so much, I've been using them to cater small lunches for my work team when I have the chance.  I typically get Dua's beef pho or the marinated pork with rice and egg.  I one time had the pho when the beef was chewy, and I admit it could be sliced thinner, but that's my only complaint, and the tender noodles, hearty broth, and bright basil with fresh veggies outweighs that one little negative blip.  The marinated pork is consistently delicious.  The flavors on that pork is amazing, and even though it's more food than my stomach can fit, I always try to eat the entire thing.  The spring roll that comes with the noodle dish is always crispy and tasty, too.  I keep telling myself I'm going to try the lemongrass chicken some day, but my two favorites of the pork and the pho always end up winning when it comes time to order.  Speaking of ordering, even though the restaurant is typically busy and packed during lunch, I have always had a very good customer service experience at Dua.  The service is always excellent, and the folks running the register have always kept their cool and a smile on their face.  We've recommended Dua to friends already, and we took my slightly suspicious sister and her boyfriend for a visit a couple months ago.  They'd never had Vietnamese before, and they didn't know what to expect.  They loved it, and we knew they would!  For tasty Vietnamese in Downtown Atlanta, there's no beating Dua.  There's additional seating downstairs; you can find the stairwell down the hallway near the bathrooms.  There's also a take out location two doors to the left, by the way.

Was in the mood for something that would warm my soul today; a big bowl of pho fit the bill. I was originally going to try a place that was closer to work but after reading some not-so-great reviews I decided to check this place out instead.  My friend and I got to the restaurant at 11:30 in hopes of beating the inevitable lunch rush and I'm very glad we did because by the time we were getting ready to leave, people were scrounging for seats.  I ordered the 'house' pho which adds eyeround steak, meatballs and beef flanks to your base/broth and rice noodles. Bean sprouts, basil, lime and jalapeño we're served on the side.  The restaurant has a couple of different seating areas, one being in the adjacent Boba Mocha tea/coffee/smoothie shop which is attached. The atmosphere of this dining area was on the minimalist side and was very clean; always a huge plus. Mellow EDM/pop played in the background.  Our food was served within 5 minutes or so. The soup came out perfect; just hot enough where I wouldn't burn my mouth when gulping large quantities of it. The food had a perfect balance of blandness and flavor with the added lime and jalapeño that I didn't feel any need to add hoisin sauce. The beef was ridiculously tender. Only thing I wasn't a huge fan of were the meatballs. I wouldn't say they were bad , just not may favorite in this dish.  I left the restaurant feeling satisfied and full but not gross which is usually the case when I eat Asian food. Overall, I loved it and plan to go back.

The decor is simple and the food is reasonably priced. However, it tastes amazing! I grew up on the west coast and I am picky about Asian cuisine (particularly in the south). This is definitely comparable to west coast Vietnamese places I have been. They also have decorated the basement for extra seating. It looks quite hipster down there with exposed brick and light strings. But, it is functional.  I highly recommend stopping by if you are downtown Atlanta.
Best in-town Vietnamese food.
Amazing to see the growth of the place over the couple of years. The food is still amazing! Get there early. You've been warned.
Awesome shrimp soup!!! Line is fast. Entrance at Boca and on Broad St. Two entrances.
Love it and I'm start to open more into new things

This place is my absolute favorite. I love their pho. Generally their chicken pho is my go to comfort food. But the other day I tried their spicy pho with chicken (#6) and instantly fell in love with it. You can substitute chicken with other meat or tofu. They have recently expanded their seating space so no waiting time for getting seated. Their other items are also good. But it's definitely the best pho in the neighborhood.
Quick, amazing pho! Eat here, you won't regret it!
Excellent!  Great lunch spot.

If you're going for lunch on a weekday, you'll need to go around 11:30 because this place gets crowded. Don't be alarmed by the line, it moves quickly. There's extra seating to the back and downstairs. Friendly staff and good service. Recommend #C2 Chicken Dish if you want Rice or any of the Pho soups if you like nooodes
The best Pho in the city.
Wow!!!!

🍲 Not big into Pho but this spot is a hidden gem. A lot of GSU students eat here regularly. It’s very bland atmosphere upstairs but then I realized the dining area is downstairs. There’s two places you can go a more well lit area on the left downstairs or the more dim Lit area to the right. I suggest the dim lit area. Feels like your in an underground nyc restaurant. But the Pho was great. Ordered it with chicken + egg rolls for appetizers. Will definitely return soon
I tried Vietnamese food for the first time, this place was really cool great food, not very oily at all I would like to dine in next time. The only negative they close to early 5 p.m. is too early!

This strip has so many great restaurants, but Dua is my favorite.  A little pricey for pho, but all their dishes are wonderful and the portions are very generous.

Today I walked in and picked up my order and when I got to work I noticed it was not chicken it was tofu! I don't ear tofu so I did not order tofu. I called back and received the worst customer service ever from an employee names Dominique. I'm sure it won't stop their business by losing mine but I will not be back!

Great fresh food.
Best food ever. I graduated from GSU  and still drive  to there to get food. It is worth it .

We used to come here at least couple times a week. Food was nice as well as a service. There were big lines, but time was worth eat. During the last 3-4 months they radically changed. Even the ownership and most of the people remained the same as it seems to be, but the quality of food and service just not good now. They have very little shrimps in my soup now, not as it used too be. Food became too oily and salad just spoiled- like it came from couple days ago or person ahead of me who didn't finish that salad. I hate to write negative reviews as it hurts business I know it as a business owner. But I not just upset,  I am hungry after purchasing the food (the price of which increased by the way). And as I always take to go, i cant come back and complain personally. Also I noticed there are no lines any more. May be other people also see the difference between before and after.
Charming little downtown noodle house. The food was fresh and bright and I'll definitely be returning.
